            <p>The name Kidapawan is derived from the Manobo words Tida (spring) and Pawan (highland), hence, A Spring in the Highland. Its first settlers were predominantly Manobos, the City’s early settlers. The influx of Christian settlers from Luzon and the Visayas has resulted in the evolution of the word Tidapawan to Kidapawan.</p>
            <p>Originally a district of Pikit, it was declared as a separate municipality on August 18, 1947. On February 12, 1998, former President Fidel Ramos signed Republic Act No. 8500 declaring Kidapawan a component city of the Province of Cotabato which was finally ratified on March 25, 1998.</p>
            <p>Kidapawan City plays a pivotal role in the economic develop- ment of the province and its adjacent areas. It is the commercial and trading hub of six neighboring towns, and is strategically surrounded by cities of Davao, Digos, Tacurong, and General Santos.</p>
            <p>All development efforts are geared towards establishing Kidapawan City as the province’s major service center that is linked to increased agricultural productivity, food sufficiency and agri-based industrialization. Envisioned as a Fruit City, the City strives to be livable, providing sufficient economic opportunities in a sustainable environment propelled by a God-centered and empowered constituency under an effective, dynamic and gender-sensitive leadership.</p>


